
[1]gallon

   GAL'LON, n. [Law L. galona.] A measure of capacity for dry or liquid
   things, but usually for liquids, containing four quarts. But the gallon
   is not in all cases of uniform contents or dimensions. The gallon of
   wine contains 231 cubic inches, or eight pounds avordupois of pure
   water. The gallon of beer and ale contains 281 cubic inches, or ten
   pounds three ounces and a quarter avordupois of water; and the gallon
   of corn, meal, &c., 272 1/4 cubic inches, or nine pounds thirteen
   ounces of pure water.
